snippet.textDisplay: I don't know if it's just me, but god the graphics card market has gone to absolute shit over the last few years. AMD hasn't dropped a compelling product in far too long and I don't know if they'll ever get back on their feet at this point, while Novideo continues to exert their monopolistic dominance whilst simultaneously also not creating a particularly interesting product. We haven't even had any decent performance gains over the years! I understand that developing a product as complex as a graphics card is incredibly challenging, but it's really sad to see, and I'm still pessimistic that Raja-lead Intel will do anything worthwhile, either.
snippet.textOriginal: I don't know if it's just me, but god the graphics card market has gone to absolute shit over the last few years. snippet.textDisplay:
I guess its time to uograde just so I can keep modding.
have had a 1070 OC to just under 2100 mhz for almost 3 years now giving me performance that could give a 1080 a run for it's money in some areas.
It could always run vanilla games at max settings in 1440 and some even in 4k but the thing is I don't play vanilla games and the more I mod the less it can handle them.
Skyrim for example I can play vanilla in 4k at max settings around 60 FPS but once I get about 400 4k texture mods in i get knocked down to about 50 FPS on 1080p.
GTAV I can play 1440p 60 FPS vanilla max settings but with NVR,PRSA,VisualV, and MVGA I get knocked down to 40 FPS at 1080p.

I don't understand how the rx 570 didn't walk away with the 100-150 dollar recommendation. the 1650 super isn't even in that price bracket and trades blows with a 115 dollar gpu. It even uses the same power connectors or close enough that any power supply worth its salt is gonna be able to power it. I cannot reccomend the 1650 super at its current pricing at all. in a 500 dollar computer that is the difference between going from a 2200g to a 2600. Now you tell me who is going to have the better gaming experience? The person with the 2200g and 1650 super? or the 2600 and rx 570?

snippet.textDisplay: This is a silly video. 99% of users are going to want performance over Nvidia's marketing gimmicks that you're calling "features" here. RTX doesn't do ray tracing well anyway, so there's no reason to buy an RTX card. And what percentage of the market is going to be using the encoder? Basically nobody. It's easy to say that the 5700 and 5700XT are a much better value at their price point. You can also argue that you'd be better keeping the extra $100 that you'd spend on a 2070 Super and getting a 5700XT instead, because you'd be paying an extra $100 for the Nvidia card for only a marginal performance gain that wouldn't be noticeable anyway. I'm getting sick of youtubers thinking that since they use computers for heavy productivity workloads that everyone else does too. The vast majority of people buying graphics cards are just people who want to play games. The percentage of the market that would use the encoder or use a gpu for any production workload is extremely small, so to put a card above another because it's better at productivity is kind of ridiculous.
